\name{novo_boot_ci}
\alias{novo_boot_ci}
\alias{print.novo_boot_ci}
\title{Novometric bootstrap CI from a fixed 2x2 confusion matrix}
\description{
Estimates the precision of an observed binary classification effect by
comparing model and chance distributions via permutation/resampling bootstrap.
Based on the NOVOboot methodology (Yarnold 2020; Yarnold & Soltysik 2016).

\strong{Fixed-confusion bootstrap:} This function samples from the observed
confusion matrix structure.  It does \emph{not} refit ODA or CTA models and
does \emph{not} estimate model-selection variability.  The model distribution
is generated by resampling paired (actual, predicted) rows from the expanded
confusion table; the chance distribution is generated by independently
resampling actual and predicted labels, breaking their association.
Novometric significance (Axiom 1) is declared when the 95\% confidence
intervals for model and chance ESS do not overlap.
}
\usage{
novo_boot_ci(x,
             nboot       = 5000L,
             seed        = NULL,
             sample_frac = 0.5,
             probs       = c(0, .025, .05, .25, .5, .75, .95, .975, 1),
             alternative = c("two.sided", "greater", "less"))

\method{print}{novo_boot_ci}(x, \dots)
}
\arguments{
  \item{x}{A 2x2 integer matrix, rows = actual class, columns = predicted
    class.  Same \code{[actual, predicted]} convention as
    \code{training_confusion} in a \code{cta_tree} and as \code{oda_confusion()}.
    Use \code{byrow = TRUE} when constructing with \code{matrix()}.}
  \item{nboot}{Number of bootstrap replicates.  Default 5000.}
  \item{seed}{Integer seed passed to \code{\link{set.seed}}, or \code{NULL}
    to use the current RNG state.  Use a fixed seed for reproducibility.}
  \item{sample_frac}{Fraction of \code{n} sampled per replicate (with
    replacement).  Default 0.5, matching NOVOboot.}
  \item{probs}{Quantile probability levels for the summary table.}
  \item{alternative}{Direction for exact Fisher p-values:
    \code{"two.sided"} (default), \code{"greater"}, or \code{"less"}.}
  \item{\dots}{Ignored.}
}
\value{
An object of class \code{novo_boot_ci}, a list with:
\describe{
  \item{\code{call}}{The matched call.}
  \item{\code{confusion}}{Input confusion matrix (integer, 2x2).}
  \item{\code{n}}{Total observations (\code{sum(x)}).}
  \item{\code{k}}{Observations sampled per replicate
    (\code{round(sample_frac * n)}).}
  \item{\code{nboot}, \code{sample_frac}, \code{probs},
    \code{alternative}}{Input parameters.}
  \item{\code{has_zero_cells}}{Logical; \code{TRUE} if any cell of \code{x}
    is zero.  Does not stop computation; NA propagates for affected metrics
    in affected replicates.}
  \item{\code{observed}}{Data frame with one row per metric.  Columns:
    \code{metric}, \code{value}.  Reports the observed (not bootstrapped)
    sensitivity, specificity, mean_pac, ess, odds_ratio, and risk_ratio
    computed directly from the input confusion matrix.}
  \item{\code{model}}{Data frame (\code{nboot} rows).  Per-replicate model
    bootstrap distributions: \code{sensitivity}, \code{specificity},
    \code{mean_pac}, \code{ess} (all in \%), \code{odds_ratio},
    \code{risk_ratio}, \code{p_value}.  \code{NA} for undefined OR/RR.}
  \item{\code{chance}}{Data frame (\code{nboot} rows).  Same columns as
    \code{model}.  Generated by independently resampling actual and predicted
    labels (null of no classification association).}
  \item{\code{quantiles}}{Data frame (\code{length(probs)} rows).  Quantiles
    of each metric for model and chance across all replicates, including
    \code{p_value_model} and \code{p_value_chance}.}
  \item{\code{ci}}{Data frame (one row per metric).  Fixed 95\% CI bounds
    (2.5th and 97.5th percentiles) for model and chance.  Columns:
    \code{metric}, \code{model_lower}, \code{model_upper},
    \code{chance_lower}, \code{chance_upper}, \code{overlap}.}
  \item{\code{significant}}{Logical scalar.  \code{TRUE} if the ESS model
    95\% CI lower bound exceeds the ESS chance 95\% CI upper bound —
    novometric Axiom 1 CI non-overlap criterion.}
}
}
\details{
\strong{Model distribution:} The input confusion matrix is expanded to
\code{n} paired (actual, predicted) observation rows.  For each replicate,
\code{k} row indices are drawn with replacement, preserving the observed
(actual, predicted) joint distribution.  This mirrors the NOVOboot
row-resampling approach.

\strong{Chance distribution:} Actual and predicted labels are resampled
independently for each replicate, breaking any association between them.
This generates the null distribution against which the model effect is
compared.

\strong{p-values:} An exact 2x2 Fisher p-value is computed for every
replicate confusion matrix for both model and chance distributions.  These
form precision distributions and complement the CI non-overlap criterion;
they are not a substitute for it.

\strong{Novometric Axiom 1:} A statistically significant effect exists when
the exact discrete confidence intervals for model and chance performance do
not overlap.  \code{significant = TRUE} indicates the ESS model 95\% CI lies
entirely above the ESS chance 95\% CI.

\strong{ESS formula:} \code{ESS(\%) = 100 * (mean_PAC - 0.5) / 0.5},
consistent with \code{\link{oda_ess_from_meanpac}}.

\strong{OR:} Diagnostic odds ratio \code{(TP * TN) / (FP * FN)}.  \code{NA}
when \code{FP = 0} or \code{FN = 0} in a replicate.

\strong{RR:} Positive predictive value / false omission rate
\code{[TP / (TP+FP)] / [FN / (FN+TN)]}.  \code{NA} when undefined.
}
\references{
Yarnold PR (2020). Reformulating the First Axiom of Novometric Theory:
Assessing Minimum Sample Size in Experimental Design.
\emph{Optimal Data Analysis} \bold{9}, 7--8.

Yarnold PR, Soltysik RC (2016). \emph{Maximizing Predictive Accuracy}.
ODA Books.
}
\examples{
# Myeloma MINDENOM=1 confusion (actual x predicted, byrow = TRUE)
conf <- matrix(c(146, 40,
                  36, 33), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE)
ci <- novo_boot_ci(conf, nboot = 200L, seed = 42L)
ci$significant
print(ci)
}
